Introduction

This report explores a data set of red wine containing approximately 1600 different kinds of wine. I’m a fan of red wine but wouldn’t consider myself very knowledgeable. The purpose of this exploration is to learn more about what chemical qualities influence overall quality of wine, rated by experts. Perhaps we can take our conclusions to the real world and do some in field testing. Before exploring the data, I think that residual sugar, alcohol level, and acidity will have the most influence on quality of wine. overall I want to learn what affects the quality of wine so that I can make more informed predictions at what kind of wine I or others would enjoy

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

Volatile acidity and quality was a really interesting one. One the largest negative correlations in our data set. After some quick research, I found out that the primary volatile acid in wine is acetic acid which is associated with the taste and smell of vinegar. This begins to explain the correlation. More volatile acid means more smelly and pungent wine which could lower quality.

After reading more about sulphates(sulphites) in wine, sulphates are used primarily as a preservative to prevent oxidization and keep the wine fresh. This is a reflection of better brewed and treated wines which would indirectly increase the quality of wine over various variables, not just sulphates.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Density and residual sugar had a correlation of 0.35 which is the strongest correlation that residual sugar has compared to other variables. Otherwise, residual sugar doesn’t have other significant interactions. This makes sense since red wine tends to have low sugar and isn’t a key component to good wine.

Density also has strong correlations with fixed acidity, and citric acid. These correlations makes sense since density is a measure of content per volume. More sugar or acidic material would make it denser than water.

Citric acid has a positive correlation with fixed acidity and negative correlation with volatile acidity. I’m not an expert on acids so I did some reading. Citric acid added before the fermentation process can turn into acetic acid which is the most common source for volatile acidity and explains the correlation. There is less citric acid because it turns into acetic acid which adds to volatile acidity. If added after the fermentation process, citric acid can complement a specific flavor and also add to its ‘fresh’ flavor.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest correlation I found was the negative correlation between pH and fixed acidity, r = -0.68. This one is straight forward since acid levels are on the lower end of the pH scale, 1-6, with neutral being at 7. Most of our wine falls within the 3-4 which is a mild acid.

Values high in fixed acidity and residual sugar tend to have a lighter shade of blue indicating higher density than the dark blue points Most of the darker blue points hang in the bottom left of our plot indicating lower values in fixed acidity or residual sugar.

Using what I learned from the EDA class on linear regression, I made a linear regression model to try to predict quality with a few more variables. I chose alcohol, citric acid, volatile acidity, sulphates, and density because they had the highest correlations to quality. While the r squared values are fairly low, this model could help when picking out wine if you know a few of the variables for that particular wine to guess how good in quality it might be.

##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 6.838799 5.542027 8.135572

To test out our linear regression model I provided a wine with hypothetical wine descriptors, not real values, to fill out all 5 of the variables I used in my r5 model. Our model predicted that the quality of our hypothetical wine would be about 6.84 with a lower bound of 5.54 and upper bound of 8.14. This seems reasonable since I tried to fill out some hypotheticalvalues that would be rated on the higher end of their respective category. It’s important to remember our low correlation values so I wouldn’t put too much faith on these predictions.

##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 7.035012 5.635479 8.434546

I did a real world test by grabbing a bottle of wine from a nearby shop trying to get a bottle high in alcohol. I found a bottle with 14.3% alcohol content. Using my r1 model, just alcohol to predict quality, we get a predicted quality rating of 7.04 which is fairly high, lower 5.64 and upper 8.43. This is fairly reasonable with our limited variable descriptor. The only way to get more info was if I had a chemistry kit to examine sulphates level, acidity, etc. Tasted the wine and I would give it a 6 to 7 myself so I agree with the model in this example. I wouldn’t expect the r1 model to be reliable in all future examples because we’re only using one variable and the correlations are fairly low.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

I’m curious how price as a variable would interact with our observations in this data set. Generally more expensive would be better but it wouldn’t be a 1 to 1 correlation.

OPTIONAL: Did you create any models with your dataset? Discuss the
strengths and limitations of your model.

I made a linear regression model using 5 variables to predict quality: alcohol, citric acid, fixed acidity, sulphates, and density. I chose these variables because they had some of the stronger correlations to quality. Since all the r squared value were generally low, I wouldn’t put a lot of confidence in this model. Another drawback to this is that it isn’t very practical to use on an everyday basis. You would need a chemistry kit that most wouldn’t have available in order to extract some of the variables needed to use this model fully. Another limitation is the way that quality is rated on this data set. The highest rating given is an 8. With how this linear regression model works, all you need is a couple outlier high values in a few of the variables to start getting predicted quality values higher than 8 when we know that no wine was rated higher than 8. Perhaps this is an issue with the critics in the data set but as it stands the linear regression model doesn’t do much to counter act potentially giving a value higher than our max reported quality values.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This plot was one of the most surprising to me. I normally had associated heavier alcohol content with poor taste but this plot showed a completely opposite trend. It’s a nice and clear plot showing that as alcohol percentage increase, quality also tends to increase. While the trend isn’t clear for values lower than and including 4, there is a positive trend from 5 and upwards.

Plot Two

Description Two

This plot summarizes the interaction between citric acid and fixed/volatile acidity. Citric acid is primarily a fixed acid while acetic acid, it’s counter- part, is primarily a volatile acid. This is because citric acid turns into acetic acid during the fermentation process which would increase the volatile acidity while lowering fixed acidity. There’s an inverse relationship here. More citric acid usually means lower acetic acid and lower volatile acidity.

Plot Three

Description Three

This last plot is a nice summary of my findings. It demonstrates the surprise alcohol and quality correlation while also including the positive effect of citric acid. This plot also separates wine into three tiers, low, middle, and high quality wine. I chose this color palette because it was really easy to see the high quality wines compared to low and medium quality. There is a nice cluster of blues for low and mid quality wine with the yellow clusters showing the high quality wine hanging out in the top right quadrant, indicating that high quality wine generally is high in alcohol content and also high in citric acid compared to other wines. ——

Overall I feel like I learned a decent amount about wine and consider myself more of a wine enthusiast. For future projects I would like to strengthen my wrangling skils so I can work with variables a bit more in depth. I had some trouble plotting variables with certain functions because I was accidentally putting quantitative variables into qualitative functions but then the plots wouldn’t come out like I wanted, etc.
